	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Andrew Murray, George MacDonald, and Charles Spurgeon (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You might not feel different the first time you read it. That's okay. The Father's love isn't a Monday-morning hype feeling — it's a foundation, and foundations get built quietly, one day at a time. Every verse you take in is your Father planting something in you that no layoff can take and no promotion can inflate.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I know the pressure you carry into work. I see the inbox that never empties, the deadline you keep replaying, the fear of being let go. And I want you to hear Me over the noise of the workday: you are Mine, and I love you right now — not the productive you, not the promoted you. You.</p><p>I'm not grading your output. I don't love you more on the days you hit your numbers or less on the days you fall short. I made you on purpose, and I called you wonderful before you ever held a job. When the week leaves you empty, come to Me — I'll give you rest and remind you who you really are. You don't have to perform for Me. You just have to come. I'm your Father, I delight in you, and no title or paycheck on earth can change that."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for your work`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for these workers — every person carrying more than their coworkers ever see. Let them hear Your whisper above the noise of the workday and the verdict of the performance review. Let them encounter Your love — not as a rule, but as a Father's delight — and know they are Your beloved son or daughter, not an employee, apart from any title or output.</p><p>Father, You delight over them whether the week goes well or falls apart. Steady them in the pressure, give them work that matters and coworkers who point them to You, and carry them through the burnout and the uncertainty when they feel like they're not enough. I pray Your protection over them — from exhaustion and the fear of failure, from the idol of productivity, from the lie that they are only as good as their last project, from the loss of identity when the work stops, and from the enemy who would steal their joy. Guard their bodies and their hearts.</p><p>Let them know there is no condemnation in You when they fall short, that they are fearfully and wonderfully made, and that nothing — no layoff, no setback, no ending — can separate them from Your love. Let them know You, their Father, as their true reward, greater than any title that fades. And may they wake up every single day knowing they are loved by their heavenly Father.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
